[[File:Okazaki-Kasumekento-Jinja-2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Torii dedicated by {{ill|lt=Honda Yasushige|Q10522159|qid=Q10522159|1=Honda Yasushige (daimyo, born 1554)}}]]
[[File:Okazaki-Kasumekento-Jinja-3.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Russo-Japanese War monument in the precincts]]

'''Kasumekentou Shrine''' (かすめけんとうじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Miyaji-chō (Okazaki)|Q107420129|qid=Q107420129|lt=Miyaji-chō|1=Miyaji-chō, Okazaki}}, {{ill|lt=Okazaki|Q242783|qid=Q242783|1=Okazaki, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It is selected as one of the {{ill|lt=100 Brilliant Okazaki Tourist Sites|Q11472991|qid=Q11472991|1=100 Brilliant Okazaki Tourist Sites}}<ref>[http://www.city.okazaki.aichi.jp/350/351/p006883_d/fil/1.pdf List of 100 Brilliant Okazaki Tourist Sites]</ref>.

=== Overview ===
It is regarded as one of the six shikinaisha in {{ill|lt=Hekikai District|Q5368803|qid=Q5368803|1=Hekikai District}} listed in volumes 9-10 of the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. In {{ill|lt=Taihō|Q1346269|qid=Q1346269|lt=Taihō|1=Taihō (era)}} 1 ({{ill|lt=701|Q23496|qid=Q23496|1=701}}), it was built enshrining {{ill|lt=Hoori|Q1051960|qid=Q1051960|lt=Hikohohodemi-no-Mikoto|1=Hoori}}. It was formerly in Nishikasume Morisaki of neighboring Kamiwada village and was therefore called Kasume Shrine, but repeated flooding moved it to the current location.

In {{ill|lt=Eien|Q1324864|qid=Q1324864|1=Eien}} 1 ({{ill|lt=987|Q23644|qid=Q23644|1=987}}), Kumano Sansho Daigongen was jointly enshrined. It is said that in {{ill|lt=Kanno|Q1145053|qid=Q1145053|1=Kannō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1350|Q6094|qid=Q6094|1=1350}}), {{ill|lt=Ashikaga Takauji|Q297107|qid=Q297107|1=Ashikaga Takauji}} donated 100 kanmon as land for Kumano Gongen.

The Okazaki domain lord {{ill|lt=Honda Yasushige|Q10522159|qid=Q10522159|1=Honda Yasushige (daimyo, born 1554)}} protected this shrine and rebuilt the honden in {{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 7 ({{ill|lt=1602|Q6727|qid=Q6727|1=1602}}). In Keichō 10 ({{ill|lt=1605|Q6741|qid=Q6741|1=1605}}), he dedicated a torii made of {{ill|lt=Shakudani stone|Q11599510|qid=Q11599510|1=Shakudani Stone}} from Echizen<ref>[http://www.city.okazaki.lg.jp/100th/topics/p020876_d/fil/41mutsumiseibu.pdf Mutsumi West School District | Okazaki Town Stories District Page | Okazaki City 100th Anniversary Site]</ref>.

A red-seal grant from {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|Q171977|qid=Q171977|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}}, dated August 28, Keichō 8 ({{ill|lt=1603|Q6735|qid=Q6735|1=1603}}), bestowed 43 koku of shrine lands. The same document says "Inugashira Shrine lands," and a red-seal grant of {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Hidetada|Q314464|qid=Q314464|1=Tokugawa Hidetada}} in {{ill|lt=Genna|Q635245|qid=Q635245|lt=Genna|1=Genna}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1617|Q6798|qid=Q6798|1=1617}}) also says "Inugashira lands," showing that in the early modern period it was publicly called Inugashira Shrine.

A munafuda for construction of the haiden in {{ill|lt=Kansei|Q1195131|qid=Q1195131|1=Kansei}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1793|Q7807|qid=Q7807|1=1793}}) has been confirmed with the inscription "Shikinaisha Kasume Shrine Inugashira Daimyōjin"<ref>Mutsumi Village Survey Association (ed.), ''Mutsumi Village History'', Nisshindō Shoten, 1926.</ref>. It appears to have started claiming identity as the shikinaisha Kasume Shrine after the late 18th century.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 4 ({{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|qid=Q7746|1=1871}}), by order of {{ill|lt=Nukata Prefecture|Q3070843|qid=Q3070843|1=Nukata Prefecture}}, it was renamed Kasumekentou Shrine. On September 18 of Meiji 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was designated a gōsha.

The honden was rebuilt in Meiji 22 ({{ill|lt=1889|Q7831|qid=Q7831|1=1889}}), and the haiden in Meiji 34 ({{ill|lt=1901|Q2035|qid=Q2035|1=1901}}).

This shrine is the starting point of the Tsutsumidōri Teyaga Otaōgi Festival<ref>{{Cite web|和書|date= |url=http://webhp.city.okazaki.lg.jp/appli/07/2shou6.pdf |title=Okazaki City Historical Landscape Maintenance and Improvement Plan - Chapter 2 Historical landscape seen in rice-cultivation rites of the Mutsumi district |format=PDF |publisher={{ill|lt=Okazaki City Hall|Q11472848|qid=Q11472848|1=Okazaki City Hall}} |accessdate=2018-4-1 }}</ref>. Children's sumo is held at the autumn grand festival.

=== Cultural properties ===
The following properties are designated cultural properties of the city<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.city.okazaki.lg.jp/1100/1109/1159/p011771.html | title=List of Okazaki City Designated Cultural Properties | publisher=Okazaki City website | date=2020-9-8 | accessdate=2021-7-19 }}</ref>.

